---
name: scljet-sql-index-maintain
description: SclJet SQL index maintenance — INSERT/DELETE/UPDATE keep the index consistent (reference sqlite validates); cross-backend byte-identical
backends: [int, js]
---

# SclJet SQL index maintenance on DML

After `CREATE INDEX`, `INSERT`/`DELETE`/`UPDATE` on the table rebuild the database compactly (table +
index, roots reassigned) so the index never goes stale — new rows are indexed, deleted rows are removed
from the index, and updating an indexed column moves its entry. Reference `integrity_check`
cross-validates the index against the table (a passing file proves consistency) and the planner uses
it. int and JS produce byte-identical output; the exact bytes are locked here.

[ByteSlice, byteSliceToList, SqliteValue, SqlInteger, SqlText, buildTableDatabase](std/scljet/index.ssc)
[executeMutation](std/scljet/sql.ssc)

```scalascript
def apply(db: ByteSlice, sql: String): ByteSlice =
  executeMutation(db, sql) match
    case Left(m) =>
      println("ERR:" + m)
      db
    case Right(next) => next

buildTableDatabase(512, 1, 1, "emp", "CREATE TABLE emp(id INTEGER, name TEXT, dept INTEGER)",
  List(List(SqlInteger(1L), SqlText("ann"), SqlInteger(20L)),
       List(SqlInteger(2L), SqlText("bob"), SqlInteger(10L)),
       List(SqlInteger(3L), SqlText("cat"), SqlInteger(30L)),
       List(SqlInteger(4L), SqlText("dan"), SqlInteger(10L)))) match
  case Left(error) => println("build-error:" + error.message)
  case Right(db0) =>
    val db1 = apply(db0, "CREATE INDEX idx_dept ON emp(dept)")
    val db2 = apply(db1, "INSERT INTO emp VALUES (5, 'eve', 10)")
    val db3 = apply(db2, "DELETE FROM emp WHERE id = 2")
    val db4 = apply(db3, "UPDATE emp SET dept = 99 WHERE id = 4")
    println((db4.length / 512).toString + ":" + byteSliceToList(db4).toString)
```
